row3: "" {
  direction: right
  style.stroke: transparent
  style.fill: transparent
  data_table: {
    shape: sql_table
    label: "Calibration Stability Metrics (quant-m3/calibration.py)"
    col1: "Samples | Scale σ² | Accuracy Drop | Status"
    row10: "10      | 2.4e-5   | 2.3% ± 1.8%   | UNSTABLE"
    row50: "50      | 8.1e-6   | 1.1% ± 0.6%   | MARGINAL"
    row100: "100     | 3.2e-6   | 0.8% ± 0.2%   | STABLE"
    row500: "500     | 1.1e-6   | 0.7% ± 0.1%   | OPTIMAL"
    row1000: "1000    | 8.5e-7   | 0.7% ± 0.08%  | DIMINISHING"
    note: "Recommendation: 100-500 samples for stable calibration"
  }
  legend: {
    direction: down
    label: "Legend"
    unstable: {
      shape: circle
      width: 16
      style.fill: "#e74c3c"
      label: "Unstable (10-50)"
    }
    converging: {
      shape: circle
      width: 12
      style.fill: "#f39c12"
      label: "Converging (100)"
    }
    stable: {
      shape: circle
      width: 12
      style.fill: "#27ae60"
      label: "Stable (500+)"
    }
  }
}
footer: |md
  **Key Insight**: Calibration scales stabilize when the calibration dataset captures the true activation distribution. Below 100 samples, random outliers dominate. Above 500 samples, diminishing returns set in. The sweet spot is **100-500 representative samples**.
| {near: bottom-center}